# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: merkle-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The **bitcoin protocol** is the set of rules that govern the functioning of bitcoin.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Its key components and principles are: a peer-to-peer decentralized network with no central oversight; the blockchain technology, a public ledger that records all bitcoin transactions; mining and proof of work, the process to create new bitcoins and verify transactions; and cryptographic security.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Users broadcast cryptographically signed messages to the network using bitcoin cryptocurrency wallet software.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] These messages are proposed transactions, changes to be made in the ledger.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Each node has a copy of the ledger's entire transaction history.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If a transaction violates the rules of the bitcoin protocol, it is ignored, as transactions only occur when the entire network reaches a consensus that they should take place.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This "full network consensus" is achieved when each node on the network verifies the results of a proof-of-work operation called *mining*.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Mining packages groups of transactions into blocks, and produces a hash code that follows the rules of the bitcoin protocol.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Creating this hash requires expensive energy, but a network node can verify the hash is valid using very little energy.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If a miner proposes a block to the network, and its hash is valid, the block and its ledger changes are added to the blockchain, and the network moves on to yet unprocessed transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] In case there is a dispute, then the longest chain is considered to be correct.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A new block is created every 10 minutes, on average.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Changes to the bitcoin protocol require consensus among the network participants.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin protocol has inspired the creation of numerous other digital currencies and blockchain-based technologies, making it a foundational technology in the field of cryptocurrencies.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Blockchain technology is a decentralized and secure digital ledger that records transactions across a network of computers.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] It ensures transparency, immutability, and tamper resistance, making data manipulation difficult.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Blockchain is the underlying technology for cryptocurrencies like bitcoin and has applications beyond finance, such as supply chain management and smart contracts.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The network requires minimal structure to share transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] An ad hoc decentralized network of volunteers is sufficient.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Messages are broadcast on a best-effort basis, and nodes can leave and rejoin the network at will.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Upon reconnection, a node downloads and verifies new blocks from other nodes to complete its local copy of the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system or a proof-of-transaction to form a distributed timestamp server as a peer-to-peer network.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This work is often called *bitcoin mining*.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] During mining, practically all of the computing power of the bitcoin network is used to solve cryptographic tasks, which is proof of work.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Their purpose is to ensure that the generation of valid blocks involves a certain amount of effort so that subsequent modification of the blockchain, such as in the 51% attack scenario, can be practically ruled out.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Because of the difficulty, miners form "mining pools" to get payouts despite these high power requirements, costly hardware deployments, and hardware under control.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As a result of the Chinese ban on bitcoin mining in 2021, the United States currently holds the largest share of bitcoin mining pools.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Requiring a proof of work to accept a new block to the blockchain was Satoshi Nakamoto's key innovation.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The mining process involves identifying a block that, when hashed twice with SHA-256, yields a number smaller than the given difficulty target.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] While the average work required increases in inverse proportion to the difficulty target, a hash can always be verified by executing a single round of double SHA-256.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] For the bitcoin timestamp network, a valid proof of work is found by incrementing a nonce until a value is found that gives the block's hash the required number of leading zero bits.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Once the hashing has produced a valid result, the block cannot be changed without redoing the work.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As later blocks are chained after it, the work to change the block would include redoing the work for each subsequent block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If there is a deviation in consensus then a blockchain fork can occur.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Majority consensus in bitcoin is represented by the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If a majority of computing power is controlled by honest nodes, the honest chain will grow fastest and outpace any competing chains.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] To modify a past block, an attacker would have to redo the proof-of-work of that block and all blocks after it and then surpass the work of the honest nodes.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The probability of a slower attacker catching up diminishes exponentially as subsequent blocks are added.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] To compensate for increasing hardware speed and varying interest in running nodes over time, the difficulty of finding a valid hash is adjusted roughly every two weeks.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If blocks are generated too quickly, the difficulty increases and more hashes are required to make a block and to generate new bitcoins.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The chips pictured have become obsolete due to increasing difficulty.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] to housing and operating large amounts of high-performance mining hardware.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin mining is a competitive endeavor.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin-specific ASICs are now the primary method of mining bitcoin and have surpassed GPU speed by as much as 300-fold.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The difficulty of the mining process is periodically adjusted to the mining power active on the network.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As bitcoins have become more difficult to mine, computer hardware manufacturing companies have seen an increase in sales of high-end ASIC products.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Computing power is often bundled together or "pooled" to reduce variance in miner income.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Individual mining rigs often have to wait for long periods to confirm a block of transactions and receive payment.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] In a pool, all participating miners get paid every time a participating server solves a block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This payment depends on the amount of work an individual miner contributed to help find that block, and the payment system used by the pool.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The environmental impact of bitcoin has been characterized in the literature as significant, particularly due to its energy use, greenhouse gas emissions, and electronic waste.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin mining, the process by which bitcoins are created and transactions are finalized, is energy-consuming and results in carbon emissions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] According to the 2025 Cambridge Digital Mining Industry Report, surveyed miners reported that 48% of their electricity came from fossil fuels and 52% from sustainable energy sources, including renewables and nuclear.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Moreover, bitcoins are mined on specialized computer hardware resulting in electronic waste.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As of 2025, several empirical studies report an association between higher bitcoin-mining electricity use and worse environmental-sustainability indicators.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin's environmental impact has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to incentives or restrictions in various jurisdictions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A 2023 study in *ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering* found potential economic benefits from using bitcoin mining at planned renewable-energy installations in the United States.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] By convention, the first transaction in a block is a special transaction that produces new bitcoins owned by the creator of the block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This is the incentive for nodes to support the network.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] It provides a way to move new bitcoins into circulation.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The reward for mining halves every 210,000 blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] It started at 50 bitcoin, dropped to 25 in late 2012, dropped again to 12.5 on the summer of 2016, and to 6.25 bitcoin in 2020.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The most recent halving, which occurred on 20 April 2024 at 12:09am UTC (with block number 840,000), reduced the block reward to 3.125 bitcoins.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The next halving is expected to occur in 2028, when the block reward will fall to 1.625 bitcoins.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This halving process is programmed to continue a maximum of 64 times before new coin creation ceases.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Each miner can choose which transactions are included in or exempted from a block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A greater number of transactions in a block does not equate to greater computational power required to solve that block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As noted in Nakamoto's whitepaper, it is possible to verify bitcoin payments without running a full network node (simplified payment verification, SPV).
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A user only needs a copy of the block headers of the longest chain, which are available by querying network nodes until it is apparent that the longest chain has been obtained; then, get the Merkle tree branch linking the transaction to its block.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Linking the transaction to a place in the chain demonstrates that a network node has accepted it, and blocks added after it further establish the confirmation.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Various potential attacks on the bitcoin network and its use as a payment system, real or theoretical, have been considered.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin protocol includes several features that protect it against some of those attacks, such as unauthorized spending, double spending, forging bitcoins, and tampering with the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Other attacks, such as theft of private keys, require due care by users.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Unauthorized spending is mitigated by bitcoin's implementation of public-private key cryptography.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] For example, when Alice sends a bitcoin to Bob, Bob becomes the new owner of the bitcoin.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Eve, observing the transaction, might want to spend the bitcoin Bob just received, but she cannot sign the transaction without the knowledge of Bob's private key.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A specific problem that an internet payment system must solve is double-spending, whereby a user pays the same coin to two or more different recipients.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] An example of such a problem would be if Eve sent a bitcoin to Alice and later sent the same bitcoin to Bob.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The bitcoin network guards against double-spending by recording all bitcoin transfers in a ledger (the blockchain) that is visible to all users, and ensuring for all transferred bitcoins that they have not been previously spent.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If Eve offers to pay Alice a bitcoin in exchange for goods and signs a corresponding transaction, it is still possible that she also creates a different transaction at the same time sending the same bitcoin to Bob.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] By the rules, the network accepts only one of the transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This is called a race attack, since there is a race between the recipients to accept the transaction first.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Alice can reduce the risk of race attack stipulating that she will not deliver the goods until Eve's payment to Alice appears in the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] A variant race attack (which has been called a Finney attack by reference to Hal Finney) requires the participation of a miner.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Instead of sending both payment requests (to pay Bob and Alice with the same coins) to the network, Eve issues only Alice's payment request to the network, while the accomplice tries to mine a block that includes the payment to Bob instead of Alice.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] There is a positive probability that the rogue miner will succeed before the network, in which case the payment to Alice will be rejected.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] As with the plain race attack, Alice can reduce the risk of a Finney attack by waiting for the payment to be included in the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Each block that is added to the blockchain, starting with the block containing a given transaction, is called a confirmation of that transaction.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Ideally, merchants and services that receive payment in bitcoin should wait for at least a few confirmations to be distributed over the network before assuming that the payment was done.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The more confirmations that the merchant waits for, the more difficult it is for an attacker to successfully reverse the transaction—unless the attacker controls more than half the total network power, in which case it is called a 51% attack, or a majority attack.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Although more difficult for attackers of a smaller size, there may be financial incentives that make history modification attacks profitable.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The cryptographic primitives employed by Bitcoin are pre-quantum and therefore vulnerable to an attack from a adversary with a cryptographically-relevant, general-purpose quantum computer.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The Bitcoin protocol uses the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) to sign and verify transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] ECDSA is vulnerable to attacks from a quantum computer due to its reliance on the security of the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The Bitcoin protocol allows senders to send Bitcoin to the hash of the recipient's public key.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The hash obscures the public key of the recipient and is therefore quantum-resistant while unspent.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] However, in order for the recipient to transact with the received bitcoin, the recipient would need to broadcast their public key.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] This broadcast could allow a quantum-enabled attacker to derive the private key from the public key and steal the Bitcoin.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Additionally, the security of the proof of work may be vulnerable to a general-purpose quantum computer with sufficient depth and stability to perform hashing.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Grover's algorithm can be applied to the hash-based proof of work of the Bitcoin protocol to quadratically reduce the time it takes to find a valid nonce.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If such quantum computers were available that could perform Grover's algorithm on a hash-based, proof-of-work blockchain, an attacker would very likely be capable of performing a 51% attack due to the massive speed-up.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Bitcoin scalability refers to the capability of the Bitcoin network to handle large amounts of transaction data on its platform.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Records (known as *blocks*) in the Bitcoin blockchain are limited in size and frequency to prioritize security and decentralization by keeping the cost of running a Bitcoin node affordable.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] With an average block creation time of 10 minutes and a block size limit of around 1 megabyte, the base layer processes an estimated 3.3 to 7 transactions per second.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Deanonymisation is a strategy in data mining in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other sources of data to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] Along with transaction graph analysis, which may reveal connections between bitcoin addresses (pseudonyms), there is a possible attack which links a user's pseudonym to its IP address.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] If the peer is using Tor, the attack includes a method to separate the peer from the Tor network, forcing them to use their real IP address for any further transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/bitcoin-protocol] The cost of the attack on the full bitcoin network was estimated to be under €1500 per month, as of 2014.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:merkle-tree/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:merkle-tree/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:merkle-tree/hash-tree-persistent-data-structure] In computer science, a **hash tree** (or **hash trie**) is a persistent data structure that can be used to implement sets and maps, intended to replace hash tables in purely functional programming.
[src:merkle-tree/hash-tree-persistent-data-structure] In its basic form, a hash tree stores the hashes of its keys, regarded as strings of bits, in a trie, with the actual keys and (optional) values stored at the trie's "final" nodes.
[src:merkle-tree/hash-tree-persistent-data-structure] Hash array mapped tries and Ctries are refined versions of this data structure, using particular type of trie implementations.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] In this conceptual guide, you'll learn about the major subsystems that IPFS is composed of, and how they work.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] While these are the key responsibilities, IPFS's functionality spans beyond these three.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Data in IPFS is addressed by its contents (content addressing), rather than a location, such as an IP address (location addressing).
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] This guide is part 3 of a 3-part introduction to the basic concepts of IPFS.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] The first part, What IPFS is and isn't, defines IPFS, while the second part, **IPFS and the problems it solves**, covers the problems with the internet and current protocols like HTTP that IPFS solves.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] All IPFS subsystems, ordered by purpose, are listed below, with links to the major subsystems discussed in this guide.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] In IPFS, data is chunked into blocks, which are assigned a unique identifier called a Content Identifier (CID).
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] In general, the CID is computed by combining the hash of the data with its codec.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] The codec is generated using Multiformats.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] IPFS uses InterPlanetary Linked Data (IPLD) to work with CIDs and content-addressed data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] IPFS uses IPLD to represent relationships between content-addressed data, such as file directories and other hierarchical structures, using a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) called a Merkle DAG.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Using IPLD for the general functionality, IPFS is able provide a more tailored, specific mechanism for representing and addressing files, directories, and their symlinks, called UnixFS.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] With UnixFS, IPFS can chunk and link data too big to fit in a single block, and use the chunked representation to store and manage the data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] IPFS uses Content Addressable aRchive (CAR) files to store and transfer a serialized archive of IPLD content-addressed data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] CAR files are similar to TAR files, in that they that are designed for storing collections of content addressed data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] IPFS uses Kademlia, a Distributed Hash Table (DHT) designed for decentralized peer-to-peer networks.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Kademlia helps you find peers in the IPFS network storing the data you are seeking.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] The Kademlia DHT can be thought of as a large table distributed across many nodes that stores information about which peers (IPs) have which data (CIDs).
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Kademlia provides a highly efficient, self-organizing system that withstands node churn.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Kademlia uses libp2p to establish connectivity.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Want to learn more about Kademlia and DHTs?
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] See the Distributed Hash Tables (DHTs) conceptual guide.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] IPFS nodes use Bitswap, a message-based, peer-to-peer network protocol for the transfer of data, that is *also* used for routing data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] With Bitswap, an IPFS node can ask any of the peers that it is connected to if they have any of the CIDs that node is looking for, all without traversing the Kademlia DHT.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Peers also store wantlists, so that if a peer receives the requested data at a later time, it can then send it to the node that originally requested.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Like Kademlia, Bitswap uses libp2p to establish connectivity.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Delegated content routing is a mechanism for IPFS implementations to use for offloading content routing to another process/server using an HTTP API.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] For example, if an IPFS node does not implement the DHT, a delegated router can search the DHT for peers on its behalf.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] The main benefit of delegated routing is that nodes are not required to implement routing functionality themselves if they do not have the computing resources to do so, or wish to build an IPFS system with a custom backend for routing.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] So, delegated routing over HTTPS provides IPFS nodes with a standard interface that allows more flexibility in terms of how content routing works.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] For further information, see the Delegated Content Routing HTTP API spec (opens new window)..
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] To quickly and efficiently discover peers in local networks, IPFS uses Multicast Domain Name System (mDNS), a type of DNS protocol that resolves human-readable internet domain names to IP names without the use of a name server.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] The use of mDNS enables quick and efficient discovery of IPFS nodes in local networks without any coordination, e.g., without internet connectivity or access to bootstrap nodes.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] In addition to routing data, nodes in the IPFS network must efficiently distribute and deliver the content addressed data, taking into account that there are some nodes in the network who already have a copy of the data, and other nodes who do not have a copy of the data, but want one.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] As discussed in How content routing works in IPFS, IPFS nodes use Bitswap, a message-based, peer-to-peer network protocol for both content routing and the transfer of data.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] With Bitswap, any peers that an IPFS node is connected to can transfer requested blocks directly to that node without needing to traverse the DHT.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Peers also store wantlists, so that if a peer receives requested data at a later time, it can then transfer it to the node that originally requested.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] HTTP Gateways allow applications that do not support or implement all IPFS subsystems to fetch data from the IPFS network using an HTTP interface.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] In its simplest form, a gateway is an IPFS Node that also exposes an HTTP Gateway API (opens new window).
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] For use cases where transfer of data over a network connection is not an option, IPFS supports the use of sneakernet to transfer content-addressed data between IPFS nodes.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Using IPFS, CAR files (discussed in How IPFS represents and addresses data) can be transferred between two network drives without any network connectivity.
[src:merkle-tree/how-ipfs-works] Because of IPFS, the data is verifiable and will have the same CID on both sides of the air gap.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:merkle-tree/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
